The basic "flaw" with the domain name system in solving "interinternet
mail routing" is that it is a database system with a tendency toward
static information. 

To a certain extent, treating the information as being static will
be a significant reason for having domain name systems in several
transport systems (ARPA, BITNET, etc.). If the data was changing
dramatically then progating the information would be a serious
problem especially if the propagation had to take less then a day
or so. The current data being used does not prevent two domain
systems from storing and retrieving data on a daily or weekly basis
on a host between the two.

Interinternet routing is a very interesting problem. I would prefer
to wait and see as other sites including CMU (we are just getting
our own BITNET mail relay working) try to deal with the problem
and get ideas and information about what people are doing exchanged.
Maybe something can be designed and specified that will work well
but somehow I believe the problem space has not been thoroughly
researched and experimented with.

Cheers,
-Rudy

